@node "new" "History"
Pine History
@{b}Pine 3.93@{ub}
 Original release from Pine3.92 sources and after applying amiga patches.
 @{b}NOTE@{ub}: This version uses an improved termcap file. If you notice that
 the arrow keys don't work, try installing the new termcap file.
 - Fixed a bug where the cursor couldn't return to the headers when editting
   the message.

@{b}Pine 3.92@{ub}
 - Original release from Pine3.92 sources and after applying amiga patches.
 - Fixed a problem with termcap emulation.
 - Fixed a problem with using the alternate editor feature in compose.
 - Fixed(?) the composer scrolling bug again. One user said he experienced it
   but I haven't been able to reproduce it.
 - Added mailto: support for AMosaic and Aweb (with script) and Voyager
 - Fixed alternate editor bug.

@{b}Pine 3.91c@{ub}
 - Recompiled to use ixemul.library version 43.0.

@{b}Pine 3.91b@{ub}
 - WB support is reinstated (thanks to gcc270)
 - Stack requirements have vanished. You can now return the stack to low values
   (thanks gcc270!)
 - Fixed the composer scrolling bug
 - Added support for AMosaic's mailto: URL. Just setenv EDITOR
   pine:pine and AMosaic will use pine for sending mail. Pine will start
   with the addressee in the To: field. PS: Don't worry that AMosaic says the
   file hasn't changed. Its just a unavoidable sideaffect.

@{b}Pine3.91a@{ub}
 - Fixed a bug that made Pine crash randomly when started from WB.
 - Now allows operability with AmiPOP and SMTPd
 - Mail now loads much faster. I think news does too but it doesn't seem to.
   (I changed a recursive routine to an iterative one.)
 - Hopefully (I really do) all the known bugs have been removed
   250K less in size!
 - AmigaGuide help - cause of the size reduction
 - Now works without AmiTCP's login
 - pine -f folder now works with Amiga-style filenames
 - Workbench support has been removed (for now - maybe restored later)
 - Fixed a bug with using SMTPd - didn't parse its headers right if timezone
   was included
 - Should work with AmiTCP 3.0b2 now. Please tell me if it doesn't.
 - Has a version string for indentification. Type @{b}version pine@{ub}
   to get Pine's version (will be 3.91 for now) and date created.

@{b}Pine 3.91@{ub}
 - Original Aminet release
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@{b}INSTALLATION@{ub}

An installer script is supplied which installs pine and copies the 
suitable files. If you hate installer scripts, you can do the following:

 assign pine: pine3.93
 assign bin: pine:bin
 assign etc: pine:etc
 assign lib: pine:lib

Also, you need to have ixemul.library 43.x in your LIBS: directory.
Ixemul.library is not including in this archive but can be found on aminet in
@{b}dev/gcc@{ub}. NOTE: Since 43.0 networking functions were fully integrated into
ixemul.library this is the minimum Pine needs to function properly.

If you have any of these assignments other
than pine: You can copy the contents of the pine3.93 directory
to the appropriate assigned directory.
@endnode

@node "Shell" " Running Pine from a shell "
@toc "using"
Since ixemul.library version 43.0, pine or any other program can automatically
detect the presence of any TCP/IP package and use it if needed. There is no
first start AmiTCP or AS225 before running Pine.

Pine will make a directory called mail in the home directory specified in the 
passwd file or the environment variable @{b}HOME@{ub}. Accompanying this archive is a
blank .pinerc file. You will need to edit this file before starting for the
first time. At the very least you will need to specify your inbox path. The 
SMTPserver and NNTPserver name are not mandatory but if you want to send 
mail/news without playing with the configuration afterwards they should be 
specified.

By default, Pine uses the IMAP protocol to access the mail server. To make 
Pine use the POP protocol, change your inbox path to {host.name/pop3}inbox. 
Using the IMAP protocol is preferred. (See doc/imap.vs.pop)

To start pine, just type @{u}pine@{uu}. To get a list of command line options, type
@{u}pine -h@{uu}.

This should be enough to get Pine up and running. Any other variable including
the inbox path and servers can be changed in the Setup-Config option from the
Main Menu screen. You can get help on any configuration item by pressing '?'.
@endnode

@node "Workbench" "Running Pine from the Workbench"
See @{"Running Pine from the shell" link "Shell" 0} for other other important configuration
options.

To run pine, just click on its icon.

There are various tooltypes with which you can configure pine. After the 
description is the equivalent option used from the CLI.

@{b}ADDRESS@{ub}=@{u}<name>@{uu} - Start Pine in the compose screen with  @{u}<name>@{uu}
in the To field.  Equivalent @{u}<name>@{uu} on the command line. 

@{b}CONF@{ub}=@{u}<filename>@{uu} - Use the file <filename> as the pine.conf file.
Equivalent to -P.

@{b}DEBUG@{ub}=@{u}<number>@{uu} - sets debug level to <number>.  By default Pine 
has a debug level of 2. This is the same as the -d option.

@{b}FOLDER@{ub}=@{u}<filename>@{uu} - Open folder @{u}<filename>@{uu}.  Equivalent to -f.

@{b}KEYSTROKES@{ub}=@{u}LIST@{uu} - Execute a comma separated list of keystrokes upon startup of
Pine. See @{"Using Keystrokes" link "keystrokes" 0} for details.

@{b}INDEX@{ub}=@{u}YES/NO@{uu} - Go directly to the index screen, bypassing the 
main menu. Equivalent to -i.

@{b}LIST@{ub}=@{u}YES/NO@{uu} - Expand list of folder collections by default.  Equivalent to
-l.

@{b}PINERC@{ub}=@{u}<filename>@{uu} - Use the file <filename> as the .pinerc file. 
Equivalent to -p.

@{b}RESTRICTED@{ub}=@{u}YES/NO@{uu} - Restricted mode, can only send mail to oneself. 
Equivalent to -r.

@{b}READONLY@{ub}=@{u}YES/NO@{uu} - Open folder in readonly mode only.  Equivalent to -o.

@{b}SORT@{ub}=@{u}SUBJECT/ARRIVAL/DATE/FROM/SIZE/REVERSE@{uu} - Tells Pine how  
to sorts folders. Equivalent to -sort.

@{b}WINDOW@{ub}=@{u}<string>@{uu} - Window setup of Pine. The window string has 
the form: CON:x/y/width/height/title/options. For more information, check
the AmigaDOS manual.
@endnode

@node "Background" "Background"
@toc "about"
@{b}BACKGROUND@{ub}

Pine(tm) --a Program for Internet News & Email-- is
a tool for reading, sending, and managing electronic messages.
It was designed specifically with novice computer users in mind, but can
be tailored to accommodate the needs of "power users" as well.  Pine
uses Internet message protocols (e.g. RFC-822, SMTP, MIME, IMAP, NNTP) and
runs on Unix and PCs and now Amigas.

The guiding principles for Pine's user-interface were: careful limitation of 
features, one-character mnemonic commands, always-present command menus, 
immediate user feedback, and high tolerance for user mistakes. It is intended 
that Pine can be learned by exploration rather than reading manuals. Feedback 
from the University of Washington community and a growing number of Internet 
sites has been encouraging.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
@toc "about"
@{b}FEATURES@{ub}
   - Integration of PGP into Pine (new for 3.93)

   - Online help specific to each screen and context.

   - Message index showing a message summary which includes the status,
     sender, size, date and subject of messages.

   - Commands to view and process messages:  Forward, Reply, Save,
     Export, Print, Delete, capture address, and search.

   - Message composer with easy-to-use editor and spelling checker.
     The message composer also assists entering and formatting
     addresses and provides direct access to the address book.

   - Address book for saving long complex addresses and personal
     distribution lists under a nickname.

   - Message attachments via the Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions
     (MIME) specification.  MIME allows sending/receiving non-text
     objects, such as binary files, spreadsheets, graphics, and sound.

   - Folder management commands for creating, deleting, listing, or
     renaming message folders. Folders may be local or on remote hosts.

   - Access to remote message folders and archives via the Internet
     Message Access Protocol (IMAP) as defined in RFC-1176 and revisions.

   - Internet news support via either NNTP or IMAP.

   - Aggregate operations, e.g. saving a selected set of messages at once.
@endnode

@node "Availability" "Availability"
@toc "about"
@{b}AVAILABILITY@{ub}

Pine, Pico, and UW's IMAP server are copyrighted, but freely available. The 
latest versions, including source code, can be found on the Internet host 
"ftp.cac.washington.edu" in the file "pine/pine.tar.Z"  (accessible via 
anonymous FTP). You can email myself  @{b}(jsshephe@undergrad.math.
uwaterloo.ca)@{ub} for the diffs to the original archive or for a standalone
archive. To try Pine out from the Internet without AmiTCP or AS225R2,  you
may telnet to  "demo.cac.washington.edu" and login as "pinedemo". There is 
also a Pine-specific Internet news group @{b}comp.mail.pine@{ub}.

For further information, send e-mail to pine@cac.washington.edu. Pine was 
originally based on Elm, but there is little if any Elm code left. Pine is the
work of Mike Seibel, Mark Crispin, Steve Hubert, Sheryl Erez, David Miller and
Laurence Lundblade* at the University of Washington Office of Computing and
Communications.  Pine and Pico are trademarks of the University of Washington.
(* Laurence is now at Virginia Tech.)

The Amiga port was done by Jeff Shepherd
<jsshephe@undergrad.math.uwaterloo.ca>

The current version of pine (along with any beta releases) can always be found
on the AmigaPine Homepage at
http://www.undergrad.math.uwaterloo.ca/~jsshephe/pine.html. (NOTE the change
of URLS for all former users.)
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Reporting Bugs"
@{b}Reporting Bugs@{ub}

If you find any bugs, please email me @{b}(jsshephe@undergrad.math.uwaterloo.ca)@{ub}
stating what the problem was. Also include you computer
setup (computer,memory, version (by typing @{b}version pine@{ub}), if you are
using a network card, etc). Also attach the .pine-debug[1-6] or the .pine-crash
file that was created while running Pine. If the bug is easily reproducible,
run pine as @{b}pine -d11@{ub} and send me email with the .pine-debug file
attached.

If you think this is a os-independent bug in Pine you can email the pine
developers by selecting the "Bug Report" option in the main menu.
@endnode

