@node "smtppost" "Using smtppost with Pine"
@toc "using"
If you want to use smtppost (eg. if you use UUCP) instead of connecting to
the  SMTPserver, leave the SMTPserver field in the pine.conf file and
your personal .pinerc file blank. By default, pine uses the command @{b}smtppost@{ub}
with arguments @{b} >NIL:@{ub}. You can override the sendmail command and/or its
arguments by setting the environment variables @{b}SENDMAIL@{ub} and @{b}SENDMAILFLAGS@{ub}
respectively.
@endnode

@node "keystrokes" "Using keystrokes with Pine"
@toc "using"
Nowhere in the Pine documentation does it tell you how to use keystrokes with
Pine. Here is how. The KEYSTROKES tooltype and the -I command line option take
a comma-separated list of keys. The list acts like you pressed a key from the
keyboard.

To simulate cursor and other special keys use the following:
 @{b}CR@{ub}		     - carriage return
 @{b}SPACE@{ub} 	     - space bar
 @{b}TAB@{ub}		     - tab
 @{b}^<key>@{ub}	     - CTRL-<key>
 @{b}F[1-10], f[1-10]@{ub}   - function key [1-10]
 @{b}UP@{ub}		     - cursor up
 @{b}DOWN@{ub}		     - cursor down
 @{b}LEFT@{ub}		     - cursor left
 @{b}RIGHT@{ub} 	     - cursor right
@endnode

@node "MIME" "Using Pine to view MIME-encoded attachments"
@toc "using"
Pine can easily send and receive email containing attachments in MIME format.
To view MIME attachments you need to do the following: Set image-viewer in
your .pinerc. I use @{b}vt >NIL:@{ub}. Take a look at the .mailcap file in the pine
directory. It contains helpful hints on setting up viewers.

If you use AMosaic, Pine can also use its mailcap file. Just delete/rename the
already existing .mailcap file and Pine will find the mailcap file in
ENV:Mosaic.
@endnode

@node "pipe" "Using Pine's pipe command"
@toc "using"
Pine has the ability to pipe attachments or messages to external commands.
Normally Pine uses csh to execute the commands. With the default distribution,
csh is actually sh, which has a limited search path for commands. To specify
pipe commands you must use the unix pathname. Eg @{b}pine:lpr@{ub} becomes @{b}/pine/lpr@{ub}.
In general @{b}device:@{ub} becomes @{b}/device/@{ub}.

An alternative is to get the excellent shell csh from Aminet. It is located in
@{b}util/shell@{ub}. This eliminates using unix pathnames.
@endnode

@node "login" "Bypassing AmiTCP's login"
You have the option of logging in with AmiTCP or bypassing it. If you use
login, Pine will take your username, full name, etc from @{u}amitcp:db/passwd@{uu} (or
@{u}inet:db/passwd@{uu} for AS225r2). If not, you can set the environment variables
HOME, USERNAME, FULLNAME to your home directory, username (for sending email)
and your full name respectively.

@{b}MAKE SURE THE ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES@{ub} are in @{b}CAPITAL@{ub} letters. Due
to a bug of some kind, using setenv with lowercase letters does not get 
recognized properly. If you find this is the case, just reset the environment 
with capital letters.
@endnode

